I've written a form validation library that use the standard ComponentModel.DataAnnotation and I've added a test page in StandaloneApp.

the library it's very simple and allow sharing models with dataannotations between blazor and backend (ref #17).

all the logic is in the ``ModelStateDictionary<T>`` class (so isn't in the form, as #970) and allow code like this

````
    var ModelState = new ModelStateDictionary<TestModel>(new TestModel())


        <div class="col-md-8 col-sm-8">
            <input type="text" bind="@ModelState[x => x.TextValue]" class="form-control" />
            <span class="text-danger">@ModelState.ValidationFor(x=> x.TextValue)</span>
        </div>

        <button onclick="@(() => this.UpdateModel())">Update model</button>


    protected virtual void UpdateModel()
    {
        this.ValidateModel();
        if (this.ModelState.IsValid)
        {
            this.ModelState.Update();
        }
    }
````

Since `<input>` tag values are always strings, ModelStateDictionary does an automatic type conversion of all values using `TypeConverter` (since it's available in netstandard2.0): putting an invalid value (like a non convertible string into number) will show an error automatically.
For now it's support short, int, long, datetime, float, double and nullable

ModelStateDictionary can update the Model via `Update(T model)` function.

The library support custom validation (with virtual `OnCustomValidateModel` and `AddModelError`).

It's a starting point (no xml comments or test cases), but seems work.

