Hi, I have a component implementing the IDisposable interface that receives an ID parameter and logs it to the console during the disposal process. 
I tried to use it in a foreach loop where an instance of the component is added for every element of a list. Adding a single item and removing it works fine and the correct ID is shown in the console. 
When more than one item is present, removing one of them correctly hides it from the UI but the console will always report the ID of the last element in the list as the disposed one.

I pushed a sample project [here](https://github.com/ghidello/IDisposableTest) but to reproduce the behaviour you can use this component:
```csharp
  // DisposableComponent.cshtml
  @implements IDisposable
  
  <li>@Id</li>
  
  @functions
  {
    [Parameter]
    int Id { get; set; }
  
    public void Dispose()
    {
      Console.WriteLine($"Disposing item {Id}");
    }
  }
```
And use it in a page:
```csharp
  @page "/"
  <p>
    <button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="@Add">Add</button>
    <button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="@Remove">Remove first</button>
  </p>
  <ul>
    @foreach (var item in Items)
    {
      <DisposableComponent Id="@item" />
    }
  </ul>
  
  @functions
  {
      private int counter = 5;
      public IList<int> Items = new List<int> {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
  
      public void Add() => Items.Add(++counter);
  
      public void Remove()
      {
        if (Items.Count == 0) return;
        Console.WriteLine($"Removing item {Items[0]}");
        Items.RemoveAt(0);
      }
  }
```
Pressing the remove button you'll see the first item disappear but the number 5 will be logged in the console by the dispose method.

Am I doing something odd?

Anyway, thank you so much for this amazing and refreshing technology!

